        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <hi rend="underline">1</hi>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Board of Editors American Hebrew</addressee>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your editorial article of <date>February 4<hi rend="sup"
                    >th</hi></date> entitled<lb/> "the mouthpiece of American Israelites" implies
                two<lb/> propositions which are both untrue and mischievous:</p>
            <p>1st. That the Jews are merely a race or nation.</p>
            <p>2d. That they are not a church.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">If these <del>propositions</del> doctrines were true, all the<lb/>
                persecutions they have suffered down to the present German<lb/> crusade would be
                explained if not justified. No<lb/> enlightened nation is bound to receive a
                compact<lb/> body of <del>
                    <add>?</add>
                </del> men owning a jurisdiction superior to<lb/> the properly constituted
                authorities of their native<lb/> land. What evidence or argument can be offered<lb/>
                to prove your views?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><del>When</del> Prior to the formation of the present Union of<lb/>
                American Hebrew Congregations, there was another<lb/> Union composed of fewer
                congregations and their<lb/> representatives were called the Board of Delegates
                of<lb/> American Israelites. In that body certain persons<lb/> claiming to be Jews
                    <del>eliminated</del> contended that<lb/> all matters affecting the welfare of
                the Jewish<lb/> church in the <placeName>United States</placeName> should be
                excluded from<lb/> discussion in order to avoid controversy between<lb/> the
                congregations and this anomalous view<lb/> finally led to its dissolution and to the
                incorporation<lb/> of its constituents with the union subsequently<lb/> formed.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <hi rend="underline">2</hi>
            </p>
            <p>This Union so formed is and ought to be the<lb/> only body speaking for American Judaism.<lb/>
                <del>and</del> You however believe that men who refuse<lb/> to affiliate with the
                Jewish church ought to<lb/> come forward as representatives of your mythical<lb/>
                Jewish race or nation and act in concert with<lb/> each other. Why should they? If
                the Jewish<lb/> church or rather the two Jewish churches, cannot<lb/> claim their
                sympathy, they ought not to per-<lb/>petuate a mere prejudice <del>in favor</del> of
                race.</p>
            <p><del>That</del> For thousands of years Judaism has stood<lb/> as a church merely and
                though its adherents<lb/> have been good subjects and citizens of many<lb/> states,
                they have adhered to their religious faith.<lb/> It is true that many adherents of
                this church<lb/> believe that in the course of its development<lb/> a state
                representing its doctrines may again<lb/> arise to disseminate morality and religion
                in<lb/> ways that we do not now foresee. This sentiment<lb/> however is a religious
                one, part of the body<lb/> of the Orthodox Jewish Church, and has no<lb/> political
                significance whatever. I may believe<lb/> that the destiny of the <placeName>United
                    States</placeName> is to unite<lb/> under one free government the whole of
                the<lb/> western continent but this not only need not<lb/> weaken my attachment to
                my country but<lb/> on the contrary tends to heighten my love for<lb/> it and my
                faith in the principles actuating<lb/> it.</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <hi rend="underline">3</hi>
            </p>
            <p>Surely such a faith would be no reason for a refusal to<lb/> affiliate with my
                fellow-Americans in all<lb/> public matters, and such a refusal by me would<lb/>
                justly forfeit my claim to be considered a<lb/> true American.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">So it is with the Jewish church. No man may<lb/> turn his back upon
                her and pretend that he<lb/> may speak for her by joining <del>
                    <add>?</add>
                </del><lb/> a health and life insurance company like the<lb/> Benai Berith and
                Kindred organizations, or<lb/> a Literary and Gymnastic association like the<lb/>
                Young Men's Hebrew Association.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To admit the contrary would be to say that<lb/> persons of the
                Jewish race constitute a separate<lb/> organization within the state for purely
                civil<lb/> and social purposes, and this would inevitably<lb/> attract hostile
                criticism and finally political<lb/> disfranchisement.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The <placeName>United States</placeName> is a free country but<lb/>
                it does not and it ought not to tolerate any<lb/> power within its territory that
                desires to keep up<lb/> race distinctions merely. The grand <add>?</add></p>
        </body>
